402–1436","1402–Male":"1402–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1436":"1436","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","about 1402":"about 1402","1376":"1376","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","aft 1400":"after 1400","Callis, Gloucester, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, England":"Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Monmouth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: locative name from Monmouth (Monmouths)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth of Monmouth was born in 1380, in Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, England as the daughter of Hugh of Monmouth. She died in 1422, in her hometown, at the age of 42, and was buried in Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1380–1422":"1380–1422","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1400–1436":"1400–1436","1402–1436":"1402–1436","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1436":"1436","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","about 1402":"umbes 1402","1376":"1376","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","aft 1400":"pärast 1400","Callis, Gloucester, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, England":"Mitcheldean, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1422":"1380–1422","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1400–1436":"1400–1436","1402–1436":"1402–1436","1402–Male":"1402–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1436":"1436","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","about 1402":"noin 1402","1376":"1376","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","aft 1400":"1400 jälkeen","Callis, Glo